International Day Against Drug Abuse and Illicit Trafficking 



Mysuru: As part of International Day Against Drug Abuse and Illicit Trafficking, City Police took out an awareness rally on the ill effects of drugs this morning. 



The awareness rally was flagged off in front of&nbsp;Kote&nbsp;Anjaneyaswamy&nbsp;Temple near the North Gate of&nbsp;Mysore&nbsp;Palace by Kannada actor Vinay&nbsp;Rajkumar.&nbsp;



In his address, he said that drugs pose danger to everyone especially youths, who are getting addicted to it.&nbsp;&nbsp;



He called upon everyone to stay away from drugs to lead a healthy life besides urging public to inform the Police if they come across anyone selling or consuming drugs.&nbsp;&nbsp;



The actor lauded the Police Department for conducting awareness rally and providing information about the ill&nbsp;effects of drugs.&nbsp;



Over 1,000 people including Police officers and staff, college students and nursing students, holding placards with messages such as ‘Say no to drugs,’ ‘Drugs destroy life,’ ‘Shun drugs to lead a healthy life’ etc., took out the rally which passed via Albert Victor Road, KR Circle,&nbsp;Sayyaji&nbsp;Rao Road, Government Ayurveda Hospital Circle, Irwin Road, Nehru Circle,&nbsp;Ashoka&nbsp;Road and Town Hall, before culminating at the starting point.&nbsp;






MLA Tanveer Sait flagging off the awareness rally at Udayagiri in city yesterday as Mysore District Chemists and Druggists Welfare Association President Kumaraswamy, Secretary Amanulla Khan, Police Officers and others look on.



City Police Commissioner Seema&nbsp;Latkar, DCP (Law and Order)&nbsp;Dr.&nbsp;Harsha&nbsp;Priyamvada, DCP (Crime and Traffic) K.S.&nbsp;Sundar&nbsp;Raj and others were present.&nbsp;&nbsp;



Vijayanagar&nbsp;Police take out awareness rally&nbsp;



Meanwhile,&nbsp;Vijayanagar&nbsp;Police took out an awareness rally in its&nbsp;jurisdiction&nbsp;yesterday.&nbsp;



Speaking on the occasion,&nbsp;Vijayanagar&nbsp;Sub-Division ACP&nbsp;Raviprasad&nbsp;said that consuming drugs will have adverse effect on the person’s health, education and family besides posing serious effect on the society which will also make way for anti-social activities.&nbsp;



He called upon the people especially youths to be aware of the ill effects of consuming drugs, stay away from it and lead a disciplined life.&nbsp;



Pointing out that this week is being&nbsp;observed&nbsp;as&nbsp;Anti Drugs&nbsp;Week &#8211; 2026, the ACP said that&nbsp;Vijayanagar&nbsp;Police will be creating awareness on drug abuse among the public, at schools and colleges by conducting various programmes.&nbsp;



Administrative Officer of&nbsp;Vijayanagar’s&nbsp;Sri&nbsp;Yoganarasimhaswamy&nbsp;Temple N. Srinivas,&nbsp;Vijayanagar&nbsp;Inspector Lava,&nbsp;Metagalli&nbsp;Inspector&nbsp;Arun&nbsp;Kumar,&nbsp;Saraswathipuram&nbsp;Police Station’s&nbsp;Ravikiran,&nbsp;Hebbal&nbsp;Police Station’s&nbsp;Lakshmikanth, Police personnel and&nbsp;students were present.&nbsp;



MLA&nbsp;Tanveer&nbsp;Sait&nbsp;flags off awareness rally&nbsp;



The Mysore&nbsp;District Chemists and Druggists Welfare Association (MDCDWA), in association with Food Safety and Drug Administration Department, JSS College of Pharmacy,&nbsp;Farooqia&nbsp;College of Pharmacy, Majestic Primary and High School and Victory Charitable Trust,&nbsp;had&nbsp; also&nbsp;organised an awareness rally at&nbsp;Udayagiri&nbsp;in city yesterday.&nbsp;






The rally,&nbsp;comprising&nbsp;students, teachers, pharmacists, healthcare&nbsp;professionals&nbsp;and members of the public was flagged off by MLA&nbsp;Tanveer&nbsp;Sait&nbsp;at&nbsp;Udayagiri&nbsp;Circle which passed on prominent roads before culminating at Majestic School in&nbsp;Udayagiri.&nbsp;



Speaking on the occasion,&nbsp;Udayagiri&nbsp;Inspector S.&nbsp;Nagesh&nbsp;highlighted the importance of creating awareness on the harmful consequences of drug abuse.&nbsp;&nbsp;



He emphasised that drug addiction can adversely affect the health, education, family&nbsp;life&nbsp;and future of young people. He urged students, parents,&nbsp;teachers&nbsp;and members of the public to remain vigilant, report suspicious drug-related activities and work together with law-enforcement agencies to build a safer,&nbsp;healthier&nbsp;and drug-free society.&nbsp;



Principal of JSS College of Pharmacy&nbsp;Dr.&nbsp;T.M.&nbsp;Pramod&nbsp;Kumar, Principal of&nbsp;Farooqia&nbsp;College of Pharmacy&nbsp;Dr.&nbsp;Nisar&nbsp;Ahmed, Principal of&nbsp;Mangaluru&nbsp;P.A. College of Pharmacy&nbsp;Dr.&nbsp;Saleemulla&nbsp;Khan, Head of the Department of Pharmacy Practice at JSS College of Pharmacy&nbsp;Dr.&nbsp;Shilpa&nbsp;Palaksha, Assistant Drugs Controller of&nbsp;Mysuru&nbsp;Circle-1&nbsp;B.V.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ashalatha, Assistant Drugs Controller of&nbsp;Mysuru&nbsp;Circle-2&nbsp; Waseem&nbsp;Ur&nbsp;Rehman&nbsp;Shariff, Secretary of Victory Charitable Trust&nbsp;Dr.&nbsp;Mohammed&nbsp;Daiyaan&nbsp;Khan, Mysore District Chemists and Druggists Welfare Association President&nbsp;Kumaraswamy, Secretary&nbsp;Amanulla&nbsp;Khan and others were present.&nbsp;&nbsp;
